Five truths about terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American policy is held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or approximately 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – a 3% increase in one month.
Over the past ten years, never have so many Americans been so concerned about terrorism, although their number is still far below the 46% recorded in the aftermath of the 9/11 attacks in 2001.
The consequences of this shift in public opinion were mainly felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
The candidacy of Donald Trump, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly inflamed (if not incendiary), has undoubtedly profited from it.
Certain politicians allow themselves to speak of the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War".
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But the presidential election candidates, as well as some media, who are adepts of the old adage "if it bleeds, it makes the front page", have exaggerated the proportions.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – have the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a sort of theater.
The terrorists worry more about holding attention and monopolizing political news than the number of victims itself.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care with its staging.
The barbaric beheadings broadcast on social networks are intended to destabilize and scandalize - and therefore to monopolize attention.
To exaggerate their consequences and make headlines with each terrorist action, it's to play the terrorists' game.
Terrorism is not the most serious threat hanging over the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills far fewer people than road accidents or smoking.
From this point of view, terrorism is not a real threat – neither major nor minor.
We are more likely to be struck by lightning than killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be assassinated by a terrorist is, according to experts, one in 3.5 million.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (a probability of 1 in 950,000), from an appliance accident (a probability of 1 in 1.5 million), by a deer or a deer crossing the road (a probability of 1 in 2 million), or in a plane crash (a probability of 1 in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year driving while texting or talking on their mobile phone.
This is several hundred times the number who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks perpetrated by disgruntled employees or than mass shootings in universities or schools.
Terrorism is not World War III.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a wave of terrorism.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a certain number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
In the sixties and seventies, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, originating from the "autonomous" left, diverted planes out of national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political leaders (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's extremist jihadists are an old political phenomenon draped in a religious costume.
Many of its leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people with a destroyed identity by globalization, who seek meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of the EI limits its scope of attraction.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, all the more so Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
The EI will ultimately be defeated, just like transnational terrorism that preceded it.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weakest of the two enemies uses the strength of the strongest to defeat it.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have managed to overthrow one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking enough citizens of a state to push them to vain actions, they may hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaida managed to lure the Americans into Afghanistan.
The EI was born in the rubble of the US-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, we need smart power.
Smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and the police with the influence power (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
The influence power is also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery and those irreducible who seek to recruit.
This is why attention to the narrative of events and the way the action of the United States is commented on social networks is also important and necessary as precision air strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the goodwill that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
Which is why the anti-Islam stance of some of the current presidential election candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorism issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It is a major piece of our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep the weapons of mass destruction out of reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap set by terrorists.
Let us not fill the theater where the actions of the brutes and thugs are being carried out.
If we leave them the great stage of our public speech, we will degrade the quality of our civic life and reveal our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
